Iran's Ministry of Health reported on March 1 that in 24 hours, the country confirmed 385 new cases, bringing the total to 978 cases, including 54 deaths, 175 discharged from hospital cured. A day earlier Iran confirmed 593 cases.

This means that Iran has surpassed Japan in the total number of confirmed cases and is second only to South Korea and Italy outside the country. Most of the confirmed cases in Iran are in the capital, Tehran, the Shiite holy city of Qom and Rasht.

Qasem Janbabaei, Iran's deputy health minister, wrote to the Dean of the National Medical School on February 29, demanding that all public, private and charitable hospitals across the country stop accepting non-emergency patients and concentrate on treating new cases of coronary pneumonia, or face legal action. Hospitals should provide round-the-clock service if necessary. Iran had previously set up at least one hospital in each province and city to treat new patients with pneumonia.

There are now more than 22 laboratories across the country equipped with test kits that can quickly test hospital samples, said Pasteur Institute Biglari, director of Iran's National Laboratory, the detection capability is tens of times higher than before.

The Iranian Medical University is working on the COVID-19 vaccine, and the new coronavirus test kit will be mass produced in the near future, according to Gadri law, deputy director of Iran's Center of strategic gravity for Science and technology. The Iranian company Ali Qolami said on February 29 that it has put the production of kits on the agenda and expects to be able to produce 150 to 200 kits per day, with each kit capable of testing 50 patients.

In an effort to curb the spread of the new coronavirus, Iran's major banks will cut working hours, schools and universities have been closed, cinemas, music halls and other public places are all closed.

The Iranian military has joined the war against the plague. According to Tasnim News Agency, the Iranian army set up "Jihadi base" (Hadi base) to combat the new crown pneumonia epidemic, and held a ceremony in Tehran on the 1st. Infantry units of the Iranian army have begun the planned disinfection of hospitals in Tehran. A Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution Officer at the Kurdistan said the guards could provide seven special vehicles to help disinfect local streets.

But the rapidly increasing number of confirmed cases continues to cause panic among the local population. A clinic in Bandar Abbas, southern Iran, was set on fire after dozens of newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia from Qom were thought to have been quarantined there, according to the Arabian Peninsula TV website. The news spread on social media and caused resentment among local people. But then the Fars News Agency dismissed the rumor.
